<div id="main_content">
	<h2>Football Game Day Update: New Knights Tradition Encourages Good Fan Behavior</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Christine Dellert
		
		<span class="date">Sept. 13, 2007</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: 196px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE955/en_US/knightcrop.jpg" height="261" width="196"  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: Jacque Brund</p>
			
			<p>The "Do the Knight Thing" for UCF fans is all about being a great fan, having fun and staying safe.</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=002400412e120743011469b630a7007770">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:tvhall@mail.ucf.edu">Tom Hall, Alcohol and Other Drug Prevention Programming</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-0869</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:cbinette@mail.ucf.edu">Chad Binette, News and Information</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-6312</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.aod.sdes.ucf.edu/REAL_pages/sport.htm">Good Sport Program</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.ucfgameday.com">UCF Game Day Web site</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.sga.ucf.edu">Student Government Association</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>The Good Sport program at the University of Central Florida is expanding this year as it moves onto campus along with the Knights home football games.</p>
<p>Previously known for prize giveaways to students promoting positive school spirit, the three-year-old program has added a new game-day pledge for fans and pre-game fan zones. This year's motto, &quot;Do the Knight Thing,&quot; is all about being a great fan, having fun and staying safe.</p>
<p>&quot;This is about setting tradition on campus,&quot; said Tom Hall, director of UCF's REAL Project, a student-led health promotion office. &quot;The focus is going to be on &quot;Do the Knight Thing,&quot; which is really about respect: Respect for each other, respect for the community and respect for yourself.&quot;</p>
<p>&quot;Do the Knight Thing&quot; and game-day Good Sport zones are collaborations among many student and staff groups, including Hall's office, Student Government Association, UCF Fraternity and Sorority Life and the Office of Student Involvement.</p>
<p>Volunteers will still be handing out Good Sport prizes, rally towels and Frisbees with the &quot;Do the Knight Thing&quot; logo and UCF temporary tattoos.</p>
<p>This year they've also created three fan zones with games and music, free pizza, Coca-Cola products, water bottles and other giveaways for Saturday's game. The spots are located at Memory Mall from 10 a.m. to 2 p.m., Lake Claire from 11 a.m. to 2:30 p.m. and the Lake Claire residential area from 12 to 2 p.m.</p>
<p>So far, SGA representatives say, students are excited about all of the on-campus events on game days. Holding the games and tailgating on campus means more opportunities for students to get involved.</p>
<p>&quot;They think it's great. It's more of a pride and tradition we're trying to start,&quot; SGA President Brandie Hollinger said. &quot;We want you to be a good UCF fan, and what a good UCF fan means is not only being responsible but being spirited and proud.&quot;</p>
<p>Plus, it's a good tailgating alternative for students who don't want to drink, Hollinger said.</p>
<p>&quot;We've got 3,000 smoothies. Weve got so many pizzas we're giving out,&quot; she added.</p>
<p>During last year's games at the off-campus Citrus Bowl, about $15,000 worth of Coca-Cola products and another $15,000 worth of pizza were handed out to students during pre-game tailgating. About 5,000 bottles of Dasani water were given away to tailgating students who pledged to be designated drivers. The same will be true this year during the six home game days, Hall said.</p>
<p>&quot;We've been working on this for three years, and it keeps getting better,&quot; he said.</p>
<p>For the past couple of weeks, Hollinger and other students have talked with classes about &quot;Do the Knight Thing&quot; and game-day events. Large banners are being installed this week with the new pledge's logo. And fliers with the five-point &quot;Do the Knight Thing&quot; pledge, which includes respecting other fans and promoting safety, have been placed in high-traffic areas.</p>
<p>The motto even spawned its own Web site, <a href="http://www.dotheknightthing.com/">www.dotheknightthing.com</a>, where pictures of students caught &quot;doing the Knight Thing&quot; will be posted, Hall said. The school also hopes to launch a &quot;Do the Knight Thing&quot; advertisement on the social-networking site Facebook.</p>
<p>UCF will also keep up its Good Sport Ambassador program, where gold-shirted faculty and staff volunteers walk around campus and help visitors with directions and other information before each game. About 40 volunteers are expected Saturday.</p>
<p>&quot;The ambassadors will be used much more heavily this year as information providers, because there will be a lot of people on our campus who haven't been here for a long time,&quot; said Rick Schell, vice provost for Academic Affairs and a Good Sport Ambassador.</p>
<p>UCF's first home game at Bright House Networks Stadium will be at 3:30 p.m. Sept. 15 against the Texas Longhorns. More information about game day plans is available at <a href="http://www.ucfgameday.com/">www.ucfgameday.com</a>. UCF has also set up a special telephone help desk that will be active on home football game days at 407-882-FANS or 407-882-3267.</p>
		
	
